Prasanna Velisetti

White Wine Quality: The dataset contains physio-chemical properties of 4898 different samples of Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine. The value for quality of wine is based on sensory data (median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts).The dataset will be used to assess the important physio-chemical properties that determines the quality of wine.There are no missig values in the dataset.

It can be seen that the distribution slightly right skewed. I wonder what happens if we combine both fixed acidity and volatile acidity as in terms of wine tasting, they both may not be distinguished.

Volatile acidity is standardized/scaled in the second graph to see if there are any outliers (>3.5)

Residual sugar distribution is clearly bimodal. One mode occurs around 1.5 and another around 12

One important thing to note here is that the residual sugar gives us a picture of unfermented sugar left in the wine. The bimodal distribution indicates that there is decent demand for both sweet wines and dry wines. Some may like to have a good taste of wine while some may want to have high alcohol. Here my assumption is that alcohol and sugar content might be realted. I would like to see if their relation.

Density ranges from 0.9871 (g / cm^3) to 1.039 (g / cm^3). We see that there is not much variation in the density. As we have the different chemical content densities given in the dataset, it is most likely that density is highly correlated with other features. So I want to explore this further in bi-variate analysis.

It is a good idea to remove the Very HIgh and Very Low quality wines from the analysis to determine which affects the wine quality as the number of datapoints are very less.

  3. Free sulfur dioxide to Total Sulfur doxide ratio

Bivariate Plots Section

Density is largely correlated (>0.8) to residual.sugar and alcohol percentage(<-0.8) As density is combined concentrations of its contents, this behaviour is expected. Density field can thus be ignored.

As discuseed earlier, there is expected to be relation between Alcohol percentage and residual sugar content. It was expected that alcohol and residual sugar would have a linear relationship given a fixed amount initial sugar content but looking at the scatter plot and the R2 value of the linear regression, the linear relationship is not apparent.This makes me think that the intial sugar content might not be the same for the wines as it depends on the type of grapes.

The variation of alcohol content decreases with increase in residual sugar content. This is because there should be limit on the intial sugar content present before fermentation.

Alcohol concentration seems to be a good indicator of wine quality as there are considerable difference in the medians between Normal and High quality wines

Higher and lower quality wines have lower residual sugar content median compared to that of normal wines.

It is observed that both Very High and Low quality wines can have lower residual sugars. Thus Residual sugar might not be good indicator of quality.It would be interesting to see if residual sugar content combined with citric acid is a good feature for quality.

Fixed acidity and Citric acid concentration on the other hand seems to be not much distinguishing the quality of wines.But we can see that the variance of citric acid decreases with increase in quality.

On the other hand volatile acidity seems to be a good feature.

Free sulfur dioxide seems to distinguishing among different qualities more than the total sulfur dioxide. We can further analyse to see if the ratio of free to total sulfur dioxide is a better feature for determining quality.

There are lot of outliers in Normal quaity wines in terms of chloride concentation. If we remove some of the outliers, we can see that with the chloride concentration quality decreases. This is expected as the wine starts to taste salty.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

  1. Alcohol concentration seems to be a good indicator of wine quality as there are considerable difference in the medians among Normal, High and very high quality wines. With the increase in Alcohol concentration, the quality of wine increases

  2. As Free sulfur dioxide increases, the quality is seen to be increasing

  3. Chlorides seem to be good indicators of wine quality.

  4. Residual sugar did not show any trend in the quality

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

  1. Checking the relation between residual sugar and alcohol concentrations. From the scatter plot, it is observed that higher the residual sugar concentration, the narrower the alcohol concentration range becomes. With the process of fermentation, natural sugar present in the grapes is converted to alcohol. Given that there should be a limit on how much initial sugar content grapes can contain, depending on how long the fermentation process goes, more and more sugar is converted into alcohol. So with a lesser residual sugar concentration, it is quite possible to have different levels of alcohol but with higher residual sugar content there is less possibility to have more alcohol content.

2)Density is strongly related to residual sugar and alcohol content. Thus Density can be removed from the list of features as there will be redundant information.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Density with residual sugar content and alcohol

Multivariate Plots Section

Free to total sulfur dioxide ratio should give us an idea on how much proportion of added sulfur dioxide is actually avaiable for protection against microbes. The trend for quality is as expected and more differentiating than if we take free sulfur dioxide itself.

As the amount of free sulfur dioxide for a given total sulfur dioxide may depend on the pH of the solution, it is plotted to check if there is any relation. While there are some trend seen for high quality wins, it is not so prominent.

As acidity and sweetness counteract each other, it is interesting to know their relationship.

We see that with increase in fixed acidity, the residual sugar content increases.

Multivariate Analysis

1)The ratio of free sulfur dioxide to total sulfur dioxide seems to be good feature that can differentiate well between diffetent qualities of wine.

2)We saw that with increase in fixed acidity, the residual sugar content increases. This shows that grapes are picked at a particular time during the ripening phase as there seems to be an importance to balance out acidity and residual sugar

Description One

It is interesting to notice how variation of alcohol percentage decreases with residual sugar. Even though there is not much linear relationship seen between alcohol and residual sugar, the extent to which alcohol percentage can vary among different wines and the residual sugar content can be related.

Description Two

Description Three

Reflection

Most of chemical properties did not correlate with each other. The dataset is biased and has very less numner of very high quality wines.A lot of background study on different chemical reactions had to be studied to understand the realtion between different parameters. While there was background study needed, most of relations are easily understandable. It was suprising that there are both low quality and very high quality wines with high concentration of residual sugar.

While different chemical properties of wines are given, there was no information on the conditions in which the grapes were grown.

There were so many outliers observed in various parts of the analysis and the reasons for such anomalies could not be explained based only on the information given.

More data needs to be collected corresponding to the low and very high quality winesto make the dataset unbiased towards different quality of wines which can then be used for predictive models to predict quality of wine given a set of physio-chemical properties.
